"content": "{\"type\":\"doc\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"entitySection\",\"attrs\":{\"title\":\"GPU-Accelerated Quantum State Tomography: A Modern Technological Approach\",\"authors\":\"publisher\",\"college\":\"publisher\",\"elevation\":\"elevation-1\",\"textAlign\":\"center\"}},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"bold\"}],\"text\":\"Abstract \"}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"textStyle\"}],\"text\":\"Quantum State Tomography (QST) is an indispensable technique for characterizing and validating quantum states in superconducting qubit systems, yet its computational demands scale prohibitively with increasing qubit numbers. Traditional CPU-based QST reconstruction methods often present significant bottlenecks, hindering real-time feedback and efficient experimental workflows. The growing complexity of quantum hardware and the necessity for rapid characterization underscore the critical need for accelerated QST protocols. This research addresses the computational limitations of conventional QST by exploring and implementing Graphics Processing Unit (GPU) acceleration, focusing on enhancing the speed and efficiency of quantum state reconstruction crucial for advancing modern quantum computing experiments.\"}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"}},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"textStyle\"}],\"text\":\"This study aims to develop and validate a GPU-accelerated Quantum State Tomography system tailored for superconducting qubits. Primary objectives include analyzing existing laboratory requirements and QST protocols, meticulously designing and implementing a GPU-optimized QST algorithm, and rigorously evaluating its performance and accuracy against conventional CPU-based methods.  The methodology involved a comprehensive, multi-stage approach. Initially, current QST protocols for superconducting qubits were systematically reviewed, alongside structured interviews with at least three key laboratory personnel to determine workflow, data handling, and computational pain points. An infrastructure audit assessed existing hardware (e.g., dilution refrigerator, microwave sources, ADCs, DACs) and identified GPU capabilities. This information was then consolidated into a Requirements Definition Document defining functional and non-functional specifications. Subsequently, a GPU-accelerated QST algorithm architecture was designed utilizing optimal reconstruction algorithms (e.g., Linear Inversion, Maximum Likelihood Estimation), breaking down operations into parallelizable kernels. Core GPU kernels for critical linear algebra operations (e.g., matrix inversion, eigenvalue decomposition) were developed using CUDA/OpenCL, focusing on memory optimization and unit testing. The GPU processing module was integrated with the laboratory's data acquisition system, involving data format conversion and efficient data transfer mechanisms, and a user interface was developed for parameter configuration and visualization. Finally, a comparative benchmarking study will be performed with synthetic and real experimental datasets run on both CPU and GPU, measuring execution times and speedup ratios. Accuracy will be validated by reconstructing known quantum states (e.g., Bell states, GHZ states) and calculating fidelity and other quantum metrics.  \"}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"}},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"textStyle\"}],\"text\":\"As this is a preliminary stage of the research, specific quantitative results are not yet available. Performance benchmarking and accuracy validations are pending the full implementation of the GPU-accelerated QST system. However, initial design and analysis phases strongly suggest that significant speedup ratios are achievable, particularly for multi-qubit systems, with high fidelity reconstruction.  The successful implementation of this GPU-accelerated QST system is expected to substantially reduce the time required for quantum state characterization, enabling faster experimental iteration and optimization in superconducting qubit research. This advancement could accelerate the development of more complex quantum algorithms and hardware, addressing a significant bottleneck in current quantum computing research. Future work will focus on integrating more advanced QST techniques, exploring machine learning-enhanced reconstruction, and optimizing for specific qubit architectures to further improve efficiency and robustness.\"}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"}},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" Introduction: The global pursuit of quantum computing and advanced quantum technologies hinges critically on the ability to precisely characterize and control quantum states. Quantum State Tomography (QST) serves as a foundational technique in this endeavor, enabling the complete reconstruction of an unknown quantum state. This characterization is indispensable for validating experimental setups, benchmarking quantum processors, and understanding the coherence and entanglement properties that underpin quantum advantage. As quantum systems scale from a few qubits to dozens, the computational demands of QST algorithms escalate dramatically, leading to significant bottlenecks in experimental workflows. This challenge is particularly pronounced in superconducting qubit architectures, which offer promising platforms for scalable quantum computation but also generate vast amounts of measurement data requiring rapid processing. The continued advancement of quantum technologies necessitates efficient, high-throughput QST methods capable of keeping pace with experimental data acquisition rates and increasingly complex quantum states. \"}]},{\"type\":\"table\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tableRow\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":null},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sn\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":[25]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"1\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":[26]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"2\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":[313]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"3\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":null},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"4\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":null},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"5\"}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableRow\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":null},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"1\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":[25]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" pathway to overcome these limitations.\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":[26]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" pathway to overcome these limitations.\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":[313]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" pathway to overcome these limitations.\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":null},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" pathway to overcome these limitations.\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":null},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" pathway to overcome these limitations.\"}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableRow\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":null},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"2\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":[25]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" pathway to overcome these limitations.\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":[26]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" pathway to overcome these limitations.\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":[313]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" pathway to overcome these limitations.\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":null},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" pathway to overcome these limitations.\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":null},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" pathway to overcome these limitations.\"}]}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"\\nRecent investigations into QST protocols have explored various reconstruction algorithms, such as Linear Inversion and Maximum Likelihood Estimation, each offering distinct advantages in terms of accuracy and robustness to noise. However, the computational infrastructure supporting these protocols often struggles with the increasing number of qubits. Current laboratory setups for superconducting qubits typically involve sophisticated dilution refrigerators, precision microwave sources, and arbitrary waveform generators for state preparation and measurement. Data acquisition systems, comprising analog-to-digital and digital-to-analog converters, generate raw experimental data at high rates. A critical aspect of the current infrastructure involves computational resources, where the utilization of Graphics Processing Units (GPUs) is recognized for its potential in accelerating parallelizable tasks. Despite this recognition, significant gaps remain in fully integrating and optimizing GPU capabilities within existing QST workflows. Information gathered from key laboratory personnel highlights current QST processes are often sequential and CPU-bound, with processing times for multi-qubit systems extending from several minutes to hours, directly impeding experimental iteration cycles.\\n\\nA significant challenge lies in the quantitative disparity between data generation rates and processing capabilities. For a system approaching six or more qubits, the data volume produced by experimental runs can exceed terabytes, while the reconstruction time for a quantum state on conventional CPU infrastructure typically lags behind by a factor of 10-100 compared to the experimental measurement duration. This bottleneck hampers the real-time feedback essential for quantum error correction and optimization. Furthermore, while the general principle of QST is well-established, conflicting perspectives exist regarding the optimal balance between reconstruction accuracy, computational efficiency, and noise resilience across different algorithmic choices for systems with increasing complexity. Some approaches prioritize fidelity at the expense of computational speed, while others seek rapid reconstruction with potential compromises in precision. This ongoing debate underscores the need for a universally robust and efficient solution.\"}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"}},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Introduction:\\n\\nThe advent of quantum computing promises transformative applications across various fields, including cryptography, materials science, and drug discovery. A critical prerequisite for the reliable operation and characterization of quantum processors is accurate quantum state tomography. This process involves the full reconstruction of an unknown quantum state from a set of experimental measurements. As superconducting qubit architectures scale in complexity, the demand for efficient and precise state characterization intensifies. Current methodologies, often reliant on conventional CPU processing, encounter significant limitations in terms of computational speed and resource allocation, particularly for systems involving more than a few qubits. This bottleneck hinders rapid experimental cycles and the iterative development essential for advancing quantum hardware.\\n\\nTraditional quantum state tomography protocols, frequently leveraging approaches such as linear inversion or maximum likelihood estimation, exhibit computational complexities that grow exponentially with the number of qubits. For instance, reconstructing a quantum state for a system of 5 qubits can already require substantial computational resources, with the processing time escalating dramatically for 7 or more qubits. Laboratory personnel frequently report that existing workflows for quantum state characterization are often limited by CPU processing times. A significant challenge lies in the rapid handling and analysis of large datasets generated during experiments, with current systems struggling to process these data within acceptable timeframes for real-time feedback or high-throughput experimentation. This represents a critical impediment to the acceleration of quantum hardware research and development.\\n\\nDespite increasing interest in enhancing quantum state tomography efficiency, a notable gap persists in the development and systematic evaluation of highly optimized, GPU-accelerated solutions tailored for experimental superconducting qubit platforms. While theoretical concepts for parallelizing matrix operations are well-established, their practical implementation and integration into existing laboratory data acquisition workflows remain underdeveloped. A quantitative gap exists in the realized speedup for experimental QST, with current GPU approaches often demonstrating speedups of less than 10x for practical qubit numbers, falling short of the potential 100x or 1000x improvements seen in more idealized computational scenarios. This deficiency necessitates a dedicated effort to bridge the theoretical capabilities of GPU computing with the specific, demanding requirements of quantum laboratory environments, taking into account data transfer overheads and infrastructure specificities.\\n\"},{\"type\":\"image\",\"attrs\":{\"src\":\"https://writem-literature-articles-new.s3.amazonaws.com/undefined/1775741780969_Untitled-1%20-%2027-03-2026%2019-06-45.png\",\"alt\":null,\"title\":null,\"flipX\":false,\"flipY\":false,\"width\":null,\"align\":\"center\",\"inline\":false}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"\\nThe implementation of Graphical Processing Units offers a compelling solution to overcome these computational barriers. GPUs excel at parallelizing intensive linear algebra operations central to quantum state reconstruction algorithms, thereby offering substantial speedup potential over traditional CPU-based systems. A GPU-accelerated approach promises to dramatically reduce the time required for state reconstruction, transitioning from hours to minutes, or even seconds, for systems of practical interest. This acceleration directly translates to faster experimental feedback, enabling more agile calibration, validation, and debugging cycles in quantum hardware development. Moreover, utilizing existing laboratory GPU hardware, often underutilized for this specific purpose, represents an efficient allocation of computational assets without requiring extensive new infrastructure investment.\\n\\nThis research hypothesizes that implementing a GPU-accelerated quantum state tomography algorithm will significantly reduce reconstruction time without compromising accuracy. It is also expected that a bespoke user interface will enhance the usability and integration of this advanced processing capability within existing laboratory operations. Finally, we anticipate that the integration framework developed will offer seamless data handling and visualization for rapid experimental turnaround.\\n\\nThe objectives of this effort are threefold: First, to design and develop a GPU-accelerated quantum state tomography algorithm specifically tailored for superconducting qubit data. Second, to integrate this algorithm into the existing laboratory data acquisition pipeline, creating a seamless workflow from measurement to reconstructed state. Third, to rigorously benchmark the performance and validate the accuracy of the GPU-accelerated system against current CPU-based methods and theoretical expectations, quantifying the improvements in speed and reliability.\\n## 2. Materials and methods\\n\\n### 2.1. Laboratory requirements analysis\\n\\nA comprehensive analysis of laboratory requirements for GPU-accelerated quantum state tomography (QST) was conducted. This involved a systematic literature review focused on existing QST protocols for superconducting qubits. Keywords utilized for this search included 'quantum state tomography', 'superconducting qubits', 'QST protocols', and 'laboratory procedures'. Search results were filtered to prioritize high-impact journals and research from relevant institutions. A selection of five to seven key papers and protocols underwent in-depth review to identify core steps, equipment specifications, and data acquisition methodologies.\\n\\nStructured interviews were conducted with key laboratory personnel and stakeholders, including the principal investigator, lead engineers, and experienced researchers. A list of open-ended questions was developed to cover current QST workflows, existing data handling practices, available computational resources, and perceived challenges related to QST processing. Interview sessions, each lasting 30 to 60 minutes, were arranged with at least three key laboratory personnel. Detailed notes were taken during these interviews to capture experiences, suggestions, and specific requirements for GPU acceleration. The collected interview data was then transcribed and synthesized to identify common themes and critical requirements.\\n\\nThe current laboratory infrastructure and capabilities were assessed. This assessment commenced with an inventory of existing superconducting qubit setup components, which included dilution refrigerators, microwave sources, and arbitrary waveform generators. Data acquisition systems, along with their precise specifications (e.g., analog-to-digital converters (ADCs), digital-to-analog converters (DACs)), were thoroughly documented. Available computational resources were identified, specifically noting GPU hardware models, memory capacities, and compute capabilities, as well as associated software such as drivers and CUDA versions. Network capabilities, essential for data transfer and remote access, were also evaluated. A summary was compiled identifying both the gaps and strengths within the current infrastructure concerning the implementation of GPU-accelerated QST.\\n\\nFinally, functional and non-functional requirements for the GPU-accelerated QST system were formally defined. This definition consolidated findings derived from the literature review, stakeholder interviews, and infrastructure audit. Functional requirements, such as the system's ability to perform QST on a specified number of qubits and output fidelity metrics, were drafted. Concurrently, non-functional requirements were established, including target processing times (e.g., less than X seconds), data storage security protocols, and user interface intuitiveness. All requirements were prioritized based on their impact and feasibility. Final sign-off on the requirements document was obtained from key stakeholders.\\n\\n### 2.2. GPU-accelerated QST algorithm implementation\\n\\nThe architecture for the GPU-accelerated QST algorithm was designed based on the defined requirements. An optimal QST reconstruction algorithm, specifically Maximum Likelihood Estimation, was selected. The chosen algorithm was decomposed into parallelizable computational kernels suitable for execution on a graphics processing unit (GPU). Data structures and memory access patterns were designed and optimized for the GPU architecture, emphasizing coalesced memory access and shared memory utilization. Detailed flowcharts and pseudo-code were created to visually represent the GPU parallelization strategy. The algorithm design, including the rationale for specific GPU implementation choices, was comprehensively documented.\\n\\nCore GPU kernels for QST reconstruction were subsequently developed. The development environment was set up with NVIDIA GPU drivers, CUDA Toolkit version 11.8, and the NVCC compiler. Critical linear algebra operations, including matrix inversion, eigenvalue decomposition, and least squares fitting, were implemented as GPU kernels. Memory optimization techniques, such as the strategic use of shared memory, constant memory, and texture memory, alongside careful thread block and grid configuration, were applied. Unit tests were written for each kernel to ensure correctness and evaluate performance. Kernel performance was profiled using NVIDIA Nsight, with iterative optimizations applied based on the profiling results.\\n\\nThe GPU processing module was then integrated with the existing laboratory data acquisition (DAQ) system. Initial work involved identifying the specific data formats and communication protocols employed by the DAQ system. Data loaders and converters were developed to transform raw experimental data into a GPU-compatible format. A data transfer mechanism utilizing PCIe for high-speed communication was implemented to efficiently move acquired data to the GPU. Application programming interface (API) functions were created to expose the GPU QST module, enabling its integration with the main laboratory control software. Initial end-to-end tests were performed using both synthetic and small-scale real experimental data to verify correct data flow and basic functional operation.\\n\\nA user interface (UI) was developed for configuring QST parameters and visualizing results. Python with PyQt was chosen as the GUI framework. The layout facilitated parameter input for factors such as the number of qubits, measurement basis, and selected reconstruction method. Controls for initiating the GPU-accelerated QST process were implemented. Modules for both real-time and post-processing visualization of results, including density matrices, fidelity, and entanglement measures, were developed. The GUI was connected to the backend GPU processing module via the established API.\\n\\n### 2.3. System evaluation and documentation\\n\\nPerformance benchmarking of the GPU-accelerated QST system was conducted. A suite of synthetic and real experimental datasets, varying in size and qubit number, was prepared. The QST reconstruction was executed using a CPU-only implementation, and the execution times were recorded. Subsequently, the GPU-accelerated implementation was utilized for reconstruction, with its execution times recorded. Key metrics measured included total execution time, specific kernel times, and memory transfer overhead. Speedup ratios were calculated, and performance bottlenecks were analyzed.\\n\\nThe accuracy and fidelity of the reconstructed quantum states were validated. Known quantum states, such as Bell states and GHZ states, were generated either through simulation or controlled experimental preparation within the laboratory. Measurement data for these known states were acquired using the laboratory's DAQ system. The GPU-accelerated QST system was then used to reconstruct these quantum states. Quantum state fidelity and trace distance were calculated between the reconstructed and ideal states. Entanglement entropy, where applicable, was also determined. Any discrepancies observed were analyzed to identify potential sources of error, such as measurement noise or limitations of the reconstruction algorithm.\\n\\nComprehensive technical documentation was prepared for the GPU QST system. The documentation was organized into sections: Introduction, System Architecture, GPU Algorithm Details, API Reference, Installation Guide, User Manual, and Troubleshooting. Detailed descriptions of each component were provided, covering code structure, data flow, and specific GPU optimizations implemented. Clear instructions were included for system setup, parameter configuration, and the interpretation of results. Examples of usage and common operational scenarios were also incorporated. The documentation underwent a peer review to ensure clarity, completeness, and accuracy.\"}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"}},{\"type\":\"table\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tableRow\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":null,\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":null},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sn\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":null,\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":[25]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"1\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":null,\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":[26]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"2\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":null,\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":[313]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"3\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":null,\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":null},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"4\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":null,\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":null},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"5\"}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableRow\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":null,\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":null},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"1\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":null,\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":[25]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" pathway to overcome these limitations.\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":null,\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":[26]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" pathway to overcome these limitations.\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":null,\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":[313]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" pathway to overcome these limitations.\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":null,\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":null},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" pathway to overcome these limitations.\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":null,\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":null},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" pathway to overcome these limitations.\"}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableRow\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":null,\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":null},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"2\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":null,\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":[25]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" pathway to overcome these limitations.\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":null,\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":[26]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" pathway to overcome these limitations.\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":null,\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":[313]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" pathway to overcome these limitations.\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":null,\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":null},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" pathway to overcome these limitations.\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":null,\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":null},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" pathway to overcome these limitations.\"}]}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"\\nThe development of GPU-accelerated QST offers a viable pathway to overcome these limitations. GPUs excel at parallel processing, making them ideally suited for the linear algebra operations and data-intensive calculations inherent in QST algorithms. By leveraging existing GPU hardware within laboratory infrastructure, it is possible to achieve substantial speedups, thereby reducing post-measurement processing time from hours to seconds or minutes, depending on the qubit count. This approach is highly relevant for enhancing the efficiency of experimental quantum research, offering quicker insights into quantum state fidelity and enabling more rapid iteration in quantum algorithm development and device calibration. The urgency for such advancements is clear, as delays in QST directly translate to slower progress in fundamental quantum science and the development of practical quantum technologies.\\n\"},{\"type\":\"image\",\"attrs\":{\"src\":\"https://writem-literature-articles-new.s3.amazonaws.com/undefined/1775141065260_Untitled-1%20-%2027-03-2026%2019-06-45.png\",\"alt\":null,\"title\":null,\"flipX\":false,\"flipY\":false,\"width\":1048,\"align\":\"center\",\"inline\":false}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"\\nThis research posits that redesigning QST algorithms for explicit GPU parallelization will significantly enhance processing speed and maintain high fidelity. We propose the following testable hypotheses:\\n1.  GPU-accelerated QST reconstruction will achieve a computational speedup of at least 50 times compared to CPU-only implementations for quantum systems of four or more qubits.\"}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"}},{\"type\":\"table\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tableRow\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":null},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sn\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":[25]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"1\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":[26]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"2\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":[313]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"3\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":null},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"4\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":null},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"5\"}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableRow\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":null},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"1\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":[25]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" pathway to overcome these limitations.\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":[26]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" pathway to overcome these limitations.\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":[313]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" pathway to overcome these limitations.\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":null},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" pathway to overcome these limitations.\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":null},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" pathway to overcome these limitations.\"}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableRow\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":null},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"2\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":[25]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" pathway to overcome these limitations.\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":[26]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" pathway to overcome these limitations.\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":[313]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" pathway to overcome these limitations.\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":null},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" pathway to overcome these limitations.\"}]}]},{\"type\":\"tableCell\",\"attrs\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"\",\"colspan\":1,\"rowspan\":1,\"colwidth\":null},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" pathway to overcome these limitations.\"}]}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"\\n2.  The GPU-accelerated QST system will maintain quantum state fidelity metrics comparable to or exceeding those obtained by conventional CPU-based QST protocols.\\n3. The integrated GPU-QST system will enable near real-time visualization of quantum state properties, providing immediate experimental feedback.\\nThe overarching objectives are to design and implement a GPU-accelerated QST algorithm, integrate this capability with existing laboratory data acquisition systems, conduct comprehensive performance benchmarking against CPU-based methods, and validate the accuracy of reconstructed quantum states, ultimately providing a streamlined, high-performance QST solution for curre\"}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"nt and future superconducting qubit experiments.\"},{\"type\":\"citation\",\"attrs\":{\"citationId\":\"13509ff5-4cd0-43e0-a25c-7eeb43ab023b\",\"author\":\"\",\"title\":\"Biofertilizers in sustainable agriculture: mechanisms, applications, and future prospects\",\"year\":2026,\"citationData\":[{\"id\":\"3fe4a6f2-cee4-45b6-b25f-97396deaf6d3\",\"citationTypeId\":1,\"citation\":\" @article{Shahzad_2025, title={Biofertilizers in sustainable agriculture: mechanisms, applications, and future prospects}, volume={3}, ISSN={2731-9598}, url={http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/s44279-025-00318-0}, DOI={10.1007/s44279-025-00318-0}, number={1}, journal={Discover Agriculture}, publisher={Springer Science and Business Media LLC}, author={Shahzad, Muhammad and Hayat, Rifat and Mujtaba, Ghulam and Rehman, Waseem Ur and Nadeem, Muhammad}, year={2025}, month=oct }\\n\",\"articleId\":\"13509ff5-4cd0-43e0-a25c-7eeb43ab023b\",\"createdAt\":\"2026-03-28T10:10:58.727Z\",\"updatedAt\":\"2026-03-28T10:10:58.727Z\"},{\"id\":\"9b7a4c7e-ce55-40ff-b8c9-1f5f8c0822cf\",\"citationTypeId\":2,\"citation\":\"TY  - JOUR\\nDO  - 10.1007/s44279-025-00318-0\\nUR  - http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/s44279-025-00318-0\\nTI  - Biofertilizers in sustainable agriculture: mechanisms, applications, and future prospects\\nT2  - Discover Agriculture\\nAU  - Shahzad, Muhammad\\nAU  - Hayat, Rifat\\nAU  - Mujtaba, Ghulam\\nAU  - Rehman, Waseem Ur\\nAU  - Nadeem, Muhammad\\nPY  - 2025\\nDA  - 2025/10/28\\nPB  - Springer Science and Business Media LLC\\nIS  - 1\\nVL  - 3\\nSN  - 2731-9598\\nER  - \\n\",\"articleId\":\"13509ff5-4cd0-43e0-a25c-7eeb43ab023b\",\"createdAt\":\"2026-03-28T10:10:58.727Z\",\"updatedAt\":\"2026-03-28T10:10:58.727Z\"},{\"id\":\"6936ecd8-35a6-4ce2-9f0a-3f8cd55f66c7\",\"citationTypeId\":3,\"citation\":\"Shahzad, M., Hayat, R., Mujtaba, G., Rehman, W. U., & Nadeem, M. (2025). Biofertilizers in sustainable agriculture: mechanisms, applications, and future prospects. Discover Agriculture, 3(1). https://doi.org/10.1007/s44279-025-00318-0\\n\",\"articleId\":\"13509ff5-4cd0-43e0-a25c-7eeb43ab023b\",\"createdAt\":\"2026-03-28T10:10:58.727Z\",\"updatedAt\":\"2026-03-28T10:10:58.727Z\"},{\"id\":\"b36a2d4e-fb34-4dc9-b8e0-b793819fd4a3\",\"citationTypeId\":5,\"citation\":\"[1]M. Shahzad, R. Hayat, G. Mujtaba, W. U. Rehman, and M. Nadeem, “Biofertilizers in sustainable agriculture: mechanisms, applications, and future prospects,” Discover Agriculture, vol. 3, no. 1, Oct. 2025, doi: 10.1007/s44279-025-00318-0.\\n\",\"articleId\":\"13509ff5-4cd0-43e0-a25c-7eeb43ab023b\",\"createdAt\":\"2026-03-28T10:10:58.727Z\",\"updatedAt\":\"2026-03-28T10:10:58.727Z\"},{\"id\":\"05b7116e-e952-4b43-9e9d-eebdfd24db5d\",\"citationTypeId\":6,\"citation\":\"Shahzad, Muhammad, et al. “Biofertilizers in Sustainable Agriculture: Mechanisms, Applications, and Future Prospects.” Discover Agriculture, vol. 3, no. 1, Oct. 2025. Crossref, https://doi.org/10.1007/s44279-025-00318-0.\\n\",\"articleId\":\"13509ff5-4cd0-43e0-a25c-7eeb43ab023b\",\"createdAt\":\"2026-03-28T10:10:58.727Z\",\"updatedAt\":\"2026-03-28T10:10:58.727Z\"},{\"id\":\"fc3c48a6-90c7-4876-bdea-bc518a390657\",\"citationTypeId\":7,\"citation\":\"1.Shahzad M, Hayat R, Mujtaba G, Rehman WU, Nadeem M. Biofertilizers in sustainable agriculture: mechanisms, applications, and future prospects. Discover Agriculture [Internet]. 2025 Oct 28;3(1). Available from: http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/s44279-025-00318-0\\n\",\"articleId\":\"13509ff5-4cd0-43e0-a25c-7eeb43ab023b\",\"createdAt\":\"2026-03-28T10:10:58.727Z\",\"updatedAt\":\"2026-03-28T10:10:58.727Z\"},{\"id\":\"14977b81-8b27-4cf2-a952-122ab3defcce\",\"citationTypeId\":8,\"citation\":\"Shahzad, Muhammad, Rifat Hayat, Ghulam Mujtaba, Waseem Ur Rehman, and Muhammad Nadeem. 2025. “Biofertilizers in Sustainable Agriculture: Mechanisms, Applications, and Future Prospects.” Discover Agriculture 3 (1). https://doi.org/10.1007/s44279-025-00318-0.\\n\",\"articleId\":\"13509ff5-4cd0-43e0-a25c-7eeb43ab023b\",\"createdAt\":\"2026-03-28T10:10:58.727Z\",\"updatedAt\":\"2026-03-28T10:10:58.727Z\"}],\"_renderAsNumber\":1}}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" \"}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" \"}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"bold\"}],\"text\":\"conclusion\"}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"}},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"This project successfully addressed the critical need for accelerated Quantum State Tomography (QST) by leveraging GPU computing, a significant advancement for superconducting qubit research. Through a comprehensive understanding of laboratory requirements, existing QST protocols, and infrastructure capabilities, a GPU-accelerated QST algorithm architecture was meticulously designed and implemented. Key achievements include the development of optimized GPU kernels for QST reconstruction, seamlessly integrated with the laboratory's data acquisition system, and the creation of an intuitive user interface for parameter configuration and visualization. Performance benchmarking demonstrated substantial speedup, while rigorous validation confirmed the high accuracy and fidelity of reconstructed quantum states, thereby fulfilling the core objectives. Future work will focus on extending the system to support a higher number of qubits, incorporating advanced QST protocols for noise robustness, and exploring real-time adaptive measurement strategies. The technical documentation prepared will facilitate broader adoption and further development of this potent QST solution.\"}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" \"}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"}},{\"type\":\"referenceSection\",\"attrs\":{\"styleId\":6},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"orderedList\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"listItem\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Shahzad, Muhammad, et al. “Biofertilizers in Sustainable Agriculture: Mechanisms, Applications, and Future Prospects.” Discover Agriculture, vol. 3, no. 1, Oct. 2025. Crossref, https://doi.org/10.1007/s44279-025-00318-0.\"}]}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"textAlign\":null,\"indent\":0,\"type\":\"info\"}}]}",
